<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>plot2d</TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>April 199</DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="plot2d4"> 2D plot (arrows style)  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
    <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>plot2d4([logflag,] x,y,[style,strf,leg,rect,nax])  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
    <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>plot2d4(y)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
    <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>plot2d4(x,y &lt;,opt_args&gt;)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
    <PARAM_INDENT>
      <PARAM_ITEM>
        <PARAM_NAME>args</PARAM_NAME>
        <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: see <VERB>plot2d</VERB>  for a description of parameters.</SP>
        </PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
      </PARAM_ITEM>
    </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
    <P><VERB>plot2d</VERB> is the same as <VERB>plot2d</VERB> but curves are plotted using arrows
    style. This can be useful when plotting solutions of an ODE in a phase
    space.</P>
    <P>
    By default, successive plots are superposed. To clear the previous plot, 
    use <VERB>xbasc()</VERB>.</P>
    <P>
    Enter the command <VERB>plot2d4()</VERB> to see a demo.</P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE>
<![CDATA[
// compare the following with plot2d1
x=[0:0.1:2*%pi]';
plot2d4(x,[sin(x) sin(2*x) sin(3*x)])
 ]]>
  </EXAMPLE>
